WEBVTT

00:00.031 --> 00:02.634
Sorry, the gradient of the log probability.

00:03.736 --> 00:21.779
Because optimal denoising theory says that for zero mean and Gaussian noise, the optimal denoising function, the optimal denoising function for zero mean Gaussian corruption is this thing right here.

00:22.419 --> 00:28.367
So it is, if you give me x and you tell me,

00:28.347 --> 00:36.366
X has been corrupted by zero mean Gaussian noise of size sigma n.

00:38.017 --> 00:43.083
then the best, and you simply tell me, give me back the original image.

00:43.143 --> 00:57.340
The best thing I can do is to take what you gave me and add this gradient of the log probability of X, if I can, if I have a model of the log probability, right?

00:57.360 --> 00:59.502
So that's the best thing I can do.

01:01.507 --> 01:04.258
And that's the best denoising function.

01:04.439 --> 01:06.427
And now you have to think a bit of in reverse.

01:06.507 --> 01:09.559
If we train a denoising auto encoder.

01:11.007 --> 01:16.173
that is going to approximate this best function that there is.

01:17.134 --> 01:20.357
So we know that the best possible denoising function is this.

01:20.697 --> 01:27.725
We train a denoising autoencoder, which in the optimal case is going to converge to the best denoising function.

01:28.025 --> 01:34.112
So if we then reformulate and we do denoising autoencoder,

01:34.092 --> 01:40.822
of x minus or x tilde minus x tilde.

01:40.842 --> 01:43.726
That is divided by the standard deviation.

01:45.008 --> 01:45.809
Sorry, the variance.

01:46.651 --> 01:55.003
That is going to give us this quantity right here, the gradient of the log probability.

